This can be simplified to:




        Suggested change











                    Integer index = nameToIndex.get(name);







                    return index != null ? index : COLUMN_NOT_FOUND;



                    return nameToIndex.getOrDefault(name, COLUMN_NOT_FOUND);






But I'm not sure this is a good design. If one refers to a column by name, it's a programming error to use a name not present in the query. I don't expect people to use this method to probe for the existence of a column.
The SqlRow class only has index-based access to values, if one uses:
int fooIndex = metadata.findColumn('foo_column');
Object value = row.getObject(fooIndex);
he will get "column index out of range: -1" instead of "column 'foo_column' doesn't exist".

